## Origins and Publication

*The Hobbit* began as a bedtime story Tolkien told to his children in the early 1930s. He eventually wrote it down, and a manuscript copy came to the attention of publisher Stanley Unwin through his son Rayner, who read it and enthusiastically recommended it. George Allen & Unwin published it in September 1937 to immediate popular success.

The book grew organically from the mythology Tolkien had been developing for years — what would become *The Silmarillion*. Bilbo's world is filled with Elvish lore, dwarven legend, and the shadow of an ancient past. Tolkien later revised the book (particularly the "Riddles in the Dark" chapter) after writing *The Lord of the Rings*, to make Gollum and the One Ring more consistent with their larger significance.

## The Story

Bilbo Baggins of Bag End is a genteel, pipe-smoking hobbit who values comfort and order above all — until the morning Gandalf the Grey arrives and sends thirteen dwarves to his door for tea. Their leader, **Thorin Oakenshield**, is heir to the Kingdom under the Mountain (Erebor), which was conquered generations ago by the dragon **Smaug**, who now sleeps atop a vast hoard of gold.

Gandalf has chosen Bilbo as the company's "burglar," and despite his protests, Bilbo finds himself swept off on the adventure of a lifetime.

